m. It situates transcultural art practices from the 1920s to the 1960s within the framework of anti-colonial movements and in relation to contemporary transcultural thinking that challenged colonial concepts of race and culture with notions of syncretism and hybridity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt, Moderny20th century. 0aCultural pluralism in art. 0aPostcolonialism and the arts. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aHale Woodruff.  aHarlem Renaissance.  aNorman Lewis.  aRabindranath Tagore.  aWinold Reiss.  aZora Neale Hurston.  aantiracism.  adecolonisation.  aglobal modernism.  atranscultural thought.1 aKravagna, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 ain2words, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packagez978311128144540uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616037940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526160379423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526160379/original  a978-3-11-128144-5  Manchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packageb2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles